I get really mad when a doctor's first reaction is to think you are faking. When I was 7 I went to the eye doctor because I couldnt see at school. Eye doc said I was faking. After a year of not being able to learn well in class, mom took me to another doctor. My eyesight was terrible, doctor asked why I didn't have glasses...

When I was 11/12 I had migraines that were not that bad, for some reason they went away after about a year. When I was 18 I was suffering from migraines again. At first it wasn't that bad but eventually I had them almost every day. During a particularly bad week I went to the ER because I couldn't do anything because of how intense the pain was. ER neurologist said it was impossible to be feeling that much pain because "there was nothing wrong with me". He gave me something for the pain and said "this should make you sleep for a few hours". Pain got a lot better after a bit, fell asleep, woke up 10 minutes later crying in pain again. The experience of that doctor not believing me made me think that I shouldn't get treatment... I suffered by myself with migraines until I was 23. I finally went to a neurologist in Brazil (Had a bad migraine while I was there visiting family) He put me on a treatment plan and within 6 months my migraines went down in intensity and frequency. after another 6 months I slowly stopped taking the meds and now I have so few migraines that I can't remember the last time I had one. Maybe 3 months ago? To think that I wouldn't have had those 4 years of pain if that neurologist in the ER had just believed me in the first place...

snippet.textDisplay:
Really respect your viewpoint on this! I was someone who was written off by doctors for 22 years and called a hypochondriac. At 22 I was officially diagnosed with ehlers-Danlos syndrome and that explained everything! I would have never knew to mention that to a geneticist I saw for a different issue had it not been for the internet. Even today, doctors are still uneducated on it and I often have to educate specialists when I see them. It’s always hard when you have to work with a doctor that can’t accept that they don’t know everything! But I am thankful to have a team that for the most part is humble. They realize that sometimes the patient with the “rare” condition of 26+ years likely has devoted more time and research into it and as a result may actually know more. You would be surprised the amount of doctors that know nothing beyond “stretchy skin and subluxations”...when stretchy skin isn’t even an absolute requirement, it’s just common.

With that said. Having been in the “not believed” category for a long time, neither of those videos bothered me. I actually found them slightly humorous. But I am years past all those issues and I am sure that when I was in the midst of not being believed, those videos may have not been funny to me at all.

snippet.textDisplay:
When I was 6 months pregnant, my husband rushed me to the er at 3 am because I was in excruciating pain, crying so much, and throwing up. My pee came out super red when I gave them my urine sample. They sent me home after a few hours (giving no pain meds or anything. The pain went away on its own, with me suffering through it). The next day, the pain came back, but I had time to think about the pain from the previous day. My kidneys! I had the symptoms of kidney stones! We went to another hospital in the area and they did a renal ultrasound and found that my kidneys were 3-4 times the size they were supposed to be, and that my kidney function was super low. I was admitted that day and was given meds under the supervision of the ob/gynecologist on staff.

I logged in to my patient portal days after discharge and saw that the initial hospital uploaded my labwork (as required by the state). THEY DRUG TESTED ME. I was in extreme pain, crying, and worried that I was in preterm labor, and they tested me for drugs and did not provide any care or tests at all. Oh , they also did a urinalysis and saw the low kidney functions and HIGH levels of blood in my urine, and still thought I was drug seeking.

I went through a few extra days of pain because they assumed that my pain was made up for drugs- I never even asked for pain meds, and actually kept turning down the meds at first when the second hospital offered it, because I didnt know how it would affect my baby.

Screw them. The nurses also kept arguing with me because I was crying and saying that the fetal monitor they were putting on me was hurting and if they can loosen it. I understand they couldnt and that I was being a little whiny about it, but still! They acted like they didnt care at all. 6 months pregnant and KIDNEY STONES. MULTIPLE. My lower back was sore for weeks after and I had to see a urologist because they kept coming back.

Medical professionals (and I am one myself) who do not care about the comfort of their patients should not be in the field.

snippet.textDisplay:
It’s hard to understand the humor in the first one if you’re not bed-side with patients like this. I’ve had a lot of patients who try to manipulate and act a way to get more medication, to get attention and pity, and to take our time away from others like it’s a game. We have patients come in and try to manipulate our emotions. That being said, we can tell who those people are. Good nurses take symptoms seriously at all times, that doesn’t mean we don’t sense if the patient is faking. The first video is a very specific example of the thoughts that may cross our mind with that kind of patient. A professional nurse would never say that in front of the patient! But we gotta let off steam somewhere and in this case it’s through humor. And honestly, this type of dark humor isn’t new. But if you’re not a med professional, you might not find it funny because it’s an unfamiliar scenario.

But even as a nurse, nurses like the second video infuriate me. Because I️ have seen nurses like that in action and actually treat their patients this way. We’re supposed to be patient advocates. The nurse can suspect different causes (bc heart attack symptoms in young adults are rare and could genuinely mean drug use) but that doesn’t mean the symptoms shouldn’t be taken seriously. Or that heart attacks in young people never happen.

I️ also think that if used wisely, medical professionals should stay online. They bring a lot of awareness and it’s a great platform for good teaching. It’s the unfortunate rare cases of out-of-context videos like the first or straight up unprofessional ones like the second that bring a bad name to medical personnel 😕

snippet.textDisplay: As someone who works in the medical field, these videos seriously just make me sad. Yes, there are times when I, or others working with patients, might feel as if a patient is "faking" symptoms or has ideas about their diagnosis that I know probably aren't correct, it is not my role to judge or make assumptions. My role is to be helpful in any possible way that I can. Or at least that's how I see it. It is never ok, in my eyes, to make fun of patients, especially on social media. Patients seek treatment for ailments whether they are truly there or not, that's kind of the exact point in seeking any type of diagnosis or treatment. What gets me the most is that these people are just acting like...well...dickheads(sorry, couldn't think of a better term for the circumstances.) Moral of the story, social media and patient care absolutely do not need to be intertwined, unless it is for educational purposes. Even then, people should tread lightly, and be aware of how they represent themselves, as well as the medical community. Plus, we could all stand to be a little kinder in general. End of rant.

I really appreciate that you brought up distrust for medical professionals. I'm 24 years old, from Sweden, and when I was 18 I started having a new throat infection every other week. I recognised that it was uncommon for me to be that ill for months and months on end, but when I told a doctor that I've never been that ill for that long before in my life he said "Well you're not that old, are you", as if I wouldn't know when a symptom / illness is uncommon for me.
I appreciate doctors and I appreciate your videos so so much, but I'm afraid that comment of his really stuck with me. I have knee problems and mental health problems, and I've had a sprained ankle that I didn't seek help for, and I've had bad coughs on and off for the last four years (since I moved to the UK), and I still haven't signed up with a GP bc I have that gnawing in the back of my head saying that a doctor wouldn't believe me anyway, that whatever I suffer from isn't "bad enough" to bother a medical professional with.
That doctor btw, in Sweden, finally believed me and allowed me to have my tonsils removed after I developed a quinsy / abscess in my throat that needed to be cut open twice. Ps. After the surgery I was told to not participate in gym class bc of the risk of bleeding, but my gym class teacher didn't believe me. What's a girl gotta do to get some trust and support lol love your channel Mike!
